3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"BingX calculates funding rates every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC using a standard premium/discount mechanism relative to the Bitcoin spot index. Funding payments occur automatically between long and short position holders, with rates typically ranging from -0.75% to +0.75% annually. The exchange uses a composite index from major spot exchanges to determine the fair value baseline for funding calculations. Position holders pay or receive funding based on their side and the prevailing rate at settlement times."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","BTC","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"BTC/USDT on BingX represents the platform's most liquid perpetual contract, offering consistent funding rate data for arbitrage analysis. The pair benefits from Bitcoin's status as the dominant cryptocurrency, ensuring reliable funding rate patterns driven by institutional and retail sentiment shifts."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"BingX BTC/USDT funding rates typically range from -0.01% to +0.03% per 8-hour period during normal market conditions. During bull runs, rates often turn consistently positive as long positions dominate, reaching +0.05% to +0.1% during peak euphoria phases. Bear markets frequently show negative funding rates as shorts accumulate, creating opportunities for long-side funding collection. Volatility spikes around major news events or options expiry often coincide with funding rate extremes, presenting short-term arbitrage windows. The platform's retail-heavy user base tends to create more predictable funding patterns compared to institutional-focused exchanges."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"BingX's funding rates occasionally diverge from larger exchanges due to its smaller market share and distinct user demographics. Positive funding rate arbitrage involves shorting BTC/USDT on BingX while holding spot Bitcoin, collecting funding payments when rates exceed the cost of hedging. Cross-exchange arbitrage opportunities emerge when BingX rates significantly differ from Binance or Bybit, though traders must account for the 0.05% taker fees on position entries. The 8-hour funding cycle allows for strategic position timing, particularly when rates are expected to normalize toward zero. Grid trading bots on BingX can be configured to automatically capitalize on funding rate reversions around key psychological levels."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"BingX's lower liquidity compared to tier-1 exchanges creates slippage risks during large arbitrage position entries or exits. The platform's 0.05% taker fees can erode profits from small funding rate differentials, requiring rates above 0.1% annually to be economically viable after costs. Funding rate arbitrage positions face basis risk if the perpetual premium moves adversely faster than funding rates adjust. Withdrawal delays or technical issues could prevent timely arbitrage exit during market stress periods. Traders should monitor BingX's insurance fund levels and overall platform stability when deploying significant capital for funding rate strategies."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often does BingX charge funding fees for BTC/USDT perpetuals?","answer":"BingX charges funding fees every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC. If you're not holding a position at these exact times, you won't be charged or receive funding payments."},{"question":"What are typical BTC/USDT funding rates on BingX?","answer":"BTC/USDT funding rates on BingX typically range from -0.01% to +0.03% per 8-hour period. During extreme market conditions, rates can reach ±0.1% or higher, creating more significant arbitrage opportunities."},{"question":"Can I use BingX's copy trading for funding rate arbitrage?","answer":"While BingX's copy trading feature allows following other traders' strategies, funding rate arbitrage requires precise timing and risk management that automated copying may not capture effectively. Manual execution is generally preferred for optimal results."},{"question":"How does BingX calculate the funding rate for Bitcoin perpetuals?","answer":"BingX calculates funding rates using the premium/discount of the perpetual price relative to a composite Bitcoin spot index. The rate is determined by the 8-hour time-weighted average premium and an interest rate component, capped at ±0.75% annually."}]}]
